abstract: Nothing could be easier or simpler than to describe yesterday's stock market. Everything rose, with just enough exceptions to prove the rule. abstract: NEW ORLEANS, March 17. -- De Heszke, M.L. Hayman's good sprinter, won the St. Patrick's Handicap to-day at 6 to 1, from a field of good horses. The five-year-old son of Lamplighter ran the six furlongs in 1:13 1-5, and was pulling up at the end, four lengths before his field. Morning Star was the public choice, but was never prominent in the running, and he finished in the ruck.

abstract: I have been surprised to see no mention made in any of our newspapers of a distinct earthquake shock which occurred in New Jersey about 1 o'clock A.M. last Monday morning. abstract: MORRISTOWN, N.J., March 26. -- The young ladies' cooking class, which has been meeting weekly for the past three months at the home of Mrs. Willis K. abstract: PINEHURST, N.C., March 26. -- Pinehurst's club for "modest golfers," the Tin Whistles, entertained during the week with a rustic german at the Holly Inn. More than thirty couples participated. The special favors were gold lace pins for the women and stick pins for the men, but for the most part they were in accord with the idea of the evening and took the form of apples, bags of nuts, monster paper sunflowers, and cabbages.

abstract: THE telephone has to be a purely urban convenience. It has become an important factor in the rural life of many sections. A talk by wire with the farmer of New England is an every-day occurrence. Calling up a plantation owner in the Blue Grass region of Kentucky has ceased to be a novelty, and, perhaps, before very long the farmers of the Far South will be saying "Hello!" to New York.

abstract: At sunset last evening the Jewish people throughout the world began the celebration of the festival of "Pesach," or the Passover. This festival was instituted to celebrate the deliverance of the children of Israel from their long bondage in the land of Egypt, and, lasting for eight days, is a season of peculiar observances.

abstract: The Board of United States General Appraisers yesterday, in a decision written by General Appraiser Lunt, denied a protest by the Stone  Downer Company of Boston, declared that the importation in question was an attempt to evade the payment of duty and to defraud the revenue, and disposed of the question as to whether wool could be mixed or not to take advantage of a lower rate of duty.

abstract: In the Democratic State Convention which meets at Albany on April 18 more than two-thirds of the 450 delegates will favor the nomination of Judge PARKER. His friends and supporters will have it in their power to pass a resolution of instructions to the New York delegates, and that power they will undoubtedly exercise.
